  <h1>3. Product Journeys: Define, Configure, and Run Changes the Chip Design Landscape</h1>
  <p><strong>SEO title:</strong> Product Journeys for Chip Design: Define, Configure, and Run Silicon Workflows</p>
  <p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> Product journeys organize chip development around outcomes instead of scattered tools, scripts, and handoffs.</p>
  <p class="tags"><strong>Suggested tags:</strong> Chip Design, Product Development, EDA, AI Workflows, Semiconductor</p>
  <p class="chiploop-intro"><strong>About ChipLoop:</strong> ChipLoop is an all-in-one agentic AI platform for silicon development. It helps engineers and small teams define, configure, and run connected chip workflows across RTL, verification, implementation, firmware/software, validation, dashboards, and product journeys. Explore ChipLoop at <a href="https://www.getchiploop.com/">https://www.getchiploop.com/</a>.</p>

  <h2>From tool runs to product journeys</h2>
  <p>Chip design has traditionally been organized around tools and teams. One team owns requirements, another works on RTL, another handles verification, another handles implementation, and so on. This creates expertise, but it also creates friction.</p>
  <p>ChipLoop introduces Product Journeys as a different way to organize work. The journey starts with the outcome: a chip block, subsystem, demo, or product-ready package.</p>

  <h2>Define, Configure, Run</h2>
  <p>The model is simple:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Define:</strong> capture product type, goal, starting point, and reference journey.</li>
    <li><strong>Configure:</strong> select stages, add apps, fill real workflow inputs, and save settings.</li>
    <li><strong>Run:</strong> execute the stages and keep logs, dashboards, workflow IDs, artifacts, and results connected.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This structure matters because real chip work is not a single generation step. It is define, configure, run, inspect, fix, and continue.</p>

  <h2>Why this is useful</h2>
  <p>Product Journeys can make common engineering paths 5 to 10 times more reusable compared with rebuilding scripts and environment setup from scratch. They also give users one view of product stages, run history, dashboards, logs, and results.</p>
  <p>Instead of asking users to remember which app, workflow, input, report, and dashboard comes next, the product journey keeps those pieces together.</p>

  <h2>The landscape shift</h2>
  <p>Product Journeys let small teams work with a product mindset from the beginning. This turns chip work from disconnected tool runs into a repeatable product development system.</p>

