  <h1>4. Debugging Chip Runs with AI-Guided Evidence</h1>
  <p><strong>SEO title:</strong> Debugging Chip Design Failures with AI-Guided Evidence</p>
  <p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> Failed synthesis, verification, or tapeout runs become easier to inspect when AI is grounded in real logs, reports, artifacts, and dashboards.</p>
  <p class="tags"><strong>Suggested tags:</strong> Chip Debug, EDA, Semiconductor, AI, Verification</p>
  <p class="chiploop-intro"><strong>About ChipLoop:</strong> ChipLoop is an all-in-one agentic AI platform for silicon development. It helps engineers and small teams define, configure, and run connected chip workflows across RTL, verification, implementation, firmware/software, validation, dashboards, and product journeys. Explore ChipLoop at <a href="https://www.getchiploop.com/">https://www.getchiploop.com/</a>.</p>

  <h2>The real debug bottleneck</h2>
  <p>When a chip run fails, the first problem is often not the root cause. The first problem is finding the right evidence. Which log matters? Which report changed? Which stage failed? Which artifact was missing?</p>
  <p>In many flows, 70 to 90 percent of early debug time can be spent locating and organizing evidence before real analysis begins.</p>

  <h2>Why AI needs evidence</h2>
  <p>AI debug becomes useful when it is attached to the run. A generic prompt can guess. A run-grounded assistant can inspect actual logs, artifact indexes, dashboards, and report summaries.</p>
  <p>In ChipLoop, Ask This Run lets users ask questions like:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Why did this run fail?</li>
    <li>What should I inspect first?</li>
    <li>Which warnings matter?</li>
    <li>What is missing for handoff?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Smart Context for focused debug</h2>
  <p>Smart Context helps reduce unnecessary context by selecting relevant evidence first. For focused run questions, it can reduce context by an estimated 60 to 85 percent compared with sending everything.</p>
  <p>This improves cost and clarity. The user sees Smart vs Full token estimates and can decide how broad the review should be.</p>

  <h2>A better debug flow</h2>
  <p>The better workflow is: detect the failed stage, open the dashboard, ask a run-grounded question, inspect the evidence, and rerun with a targeted fix. This is the practical direction for AI-assisted chip debug.</p>

