  <h1>5. Self-Repair Loops for Verification, Synthesis, and Physical Design Closure</h1>
  <p><strong>SEO title:</strong> Self-Repair Loops for Verification, Synthesis, Timing, DRC, and LVS Closure</p>
  <p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> Bounded repair loops can analyze real evidence, apply targeted changes, rerun stages, and summarize closure results.</p>
  <p class="tags"><strong>Suggested tags:</strong> Verification, Synthesis, Physical Design, EDA, AI Automation</p>
  <p class="chiploop-intro"><strong>About ChipLoop:</strong> ChipLoop is an all-in-one agentic AI platform for silicon development. It helps engineers and small teams define, configure, and run connected chip workflows across RTL, verification, implementation, firmware/software, validation, dashboards, and product journeys. Explore ChipLoop at <a href="https://www.getchiploop.com/">https://www.getchiploop.com/</a>.</p>

  <h2>What is a self-repair loop?</h2>
  <p>A self-repair loop is a controlled closure pattern. The platform reads real evidence, classifies the issue, applies a bounded repair, reruns the relevant stage, and summarizes the result.</p>
  <p>This is not blind automation. It should be limited, traceable, and reviewable. A practical starting point is 1 to 3 iterations, not an open-ended loop.</p>

  <h2>Verification closure</h2>
  <p>A verification run may compile successfully but miss coverage targets or fail a subset of tests. A closure loop can analyze failures and coverage gaps, add testcase or seed intent, update the verification plan, rerun verification, and summarize what improved.</p>

  <h2>Synthesis closure</h2>
  <p>A synthesis run may fail timing, produce warnings, or need LEC review. A synthesis closure loop can classify whether the issue is related to constraints, hierarchy, retiming, tool options, or design structure. Then it can rerun with a bounded change and report timing and LEC status.</p>

  <h2>Physical design closure</h2>
  <p>PD closure has several evidence streams:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>LEF:</strong> pin, abstract, or macro-interface issues.</li>
    <li><strong>Timing:</strong> slack, critical paths, constraints, or congestion-sensitive paths.</li>
    <li><strong>DRC:</strong> spacing, antenna, density, fill, or routing violations.</li>
    <li><strong>LVS:</strong> connectivity, missing devices, pin mismatch, or layout/netlist mismatch.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>ChipLoop is built for this because workflows, artifacts, dashboards, Ask This Run, HEM, and product journeys remain connected. That makes self-repair loops practical instead of hidden inside a black box.</p>

