  <h2>AI adoption needs trust</h2>
  <p>Chip design teams want AI leverage, but they cannot treat engineering context casually. Requirements, RTL, verification plans, constraints, timing reports, validation notes, and product strategy are valuable IP.</p>
  <p>If AI is used outside a controlled workflow, teams may get short-term productivity but lose long-term trust and governance.</p>

  <h2>What private AI workflows need</h2>
  <p>Private workflows should keep project context under team control. They should support web use, SDK use, CLI use, and automation without separating the engineering record.</p>
  <p>A practical private AI workflow needs:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Private apps and workflows.</li>
    <li>Controlled access and billing policy.</li>
    <li>Run history, dashboards, logs, and artifacts.</li>
    <li>Admin review for marketplace or shared publication.</li>
    <li>Integration into private engineering environments when needed.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where ChipLoop helps</h2>
  <p>ChipLoop supports private apps, user-created workflows, SDK/CLI access, product journeys, and run-level evidence. The goal is to bring AI into the team's process without turning it into an unmanaged side channel.</p>
  <p>A simple metric matters here: zero public IP by default for private engineering context. AI has to fit the way silicon teams work.</p>

