  <h1>9. HEM: Automatic Engineering Memory for Connected Silicon Workflows</h1>
  <p><strong>SEO title:</strong> Hebbian Engineering Memory for Self-Regulated Silicon Workflows</p>
  <p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> HEM helps ChipLoop continue from one successful workflow to the next selected engineering step while preserving evidence and dashboards.</p>
  <p class="tags"><strong>Suggested tags:</strong> Agentic AI, Semiconductor, Workflow Automation, Chip Design, HEM</p>
  <p class="chiploop-intro"><strong>About ChipLoop:</strong> ChipLoop is an all-in-one agentic AI platform for silicon development. It helps engineers and small teams define, configure, and run connected chip workflows across RTL, verification, implementation, firmware/software, validation, dashboards, and product journeys. Explore ChipLoop at <a href="https://www.getchiploop.com/">https://www.getchiploop.com/</a>.</p>

  <h2>The idea behind HEM</h2>
  <p>HEM stands for Hebbian Engineering Memory. In ChipLoop, it starts as a controlled continuation feature. When a workflow completes successfully, ChipLoop can start the next selected workflow using the completed run as context.</p>
  <p>For example, after Arch2RTL passes, HEM can continue to DQA, verification, synthesis, or tapeout depending on the enabled policy. For system flows, it can continue toward implementation or product-demo stages.</p>

  <h2>Fixed and adaptive</h2>
  <p>Fixed HEM follows a built-in policy. Adaptive HEM records successful transitions for future learning. The learning idea follows a simple Hebbian form: successful transitions become stronger signals over time.</p>
  <p>The user remains in control. HEM is disabled by default, and downstream stages can be selected before the run starts.</p>

  <h2>What the engineer sees</h2>
  <p>The root workflow shows a HEM Run Summary table. Each child workflow has its own workflow ID, status from Supabase, and an Open Dashboard link. This makes HEM feel like a compact product journey.</p>
  <p>HEM is a step toward self-regulated silicon workflows: run the next selected stage, preserve evidence, and keep engineers in control.</p>

